<DOC><DOCNO> AP881014-0288 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0740EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-14 0343</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Higher In Moderate Trading, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar rose against most currencies inmoderate European trading today in what dealers said was a reactionto the previous day's aggressive sell-off following news of asharply wider U.S. trade deficit.   Gold prices were slightly weaker in calm trading.   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar's recovery was alsopartially due to banks squaring their positions ahead of theweekend.   One trader in Rome said market sentiment generally has turnedagainst the dollar. But another said the dollar was likely toremain ``fairly stable'' between now and the U.S. presidentialelection on Nov. 8 provided there weren't any major newsdevelopments.   The dollar rebounded in Asian trading earlier in the day.Traders said the rise was sparked by remarks in Tokyo by U.S.Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan who said the group of sevenmajor industrialized nations remained committed to its policy ofcurrency stability.   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business daybegins, the dollar rose 0.27 yen to a closing 128.25 yen. Later, inLondon, it was quoted lower at 127.98 yen.   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday'srates, included: 1.8211 West German marks, up from 1.8193; 1.5405Swiss francs, up from 1.5390; 6.2170 French francs, up from 6.1995;2.0505 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0475; 1,358.25 Italian lire, upfrom 1,354.00; and 1.2065 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2084.   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost$1.7435 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7470 late Thursday.   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406.30 a troy ounce andat midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed arecommended price of $406.50. Both were down from late Thursday'sbid of $406.70.   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.30, down from $406.50 bid lateThursday.   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.40 to close at a bid $409.82.   Silver was quoted in London Friday at a bid price of $6.265 atroy ounce, down from late Thursday's $6.29.</TEXT></DOC>